{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657053"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:22:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:22:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19063"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19063","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19063"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.62,0.16,0.05,0.16,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11797"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82294"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11797","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11797"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19063"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67492"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1515"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10799"},{"type":"tags","id":"11020"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27751"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28102"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82294","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82294"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with generalised urticaria, facial swelling and difficulty breathing. These symptoms developed  about 10 minutes after eating a meal of prawns. On examination, she appears distressed. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Widespread wheals are present on her trunk and limbs. Auscultation reveals bilateral wheeze.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following types of hypersensitivity reaction best explains this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Type I","Type II","Type III","Type IV","Type V"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with anaphylaxis, which is a classic example of a Type I hypersensitivity reaction. \u003Cstrong\u003EType I\u003C/strong\u003E hypersensitivity reactions are immediate, IgE-mediated responses that occur within minutes of exposure to an allergen. When an allergen cross-links IgE bound to mast cells, it triggers the release of preformed mediators (including histamine) and newly synthesised mediators, leading to vasodilation, increased vascular permeability, bronchial smooth muscle contraction, and mucus secretion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType II\u003C/strong\u003E hypersensitivity reactions are antibody-dependent cytotoxic reactions where IgG or IgM antibodies bind to cell surface antigens, leading to cell destruction. Examples include autoimmune haemolytic anaemia and transfusion reactions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType III\u003C/strong\u003E hypersensitivity reactions involve immune complex formation and deposition in tissues, leading to complement activation and inflammation. This typically occurs over hours to days and is seen in conditions like serum sickness and systemic lupus erythematosus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType IV\u003C/strong\u003E hypersensitivity reactions are delayed, cell-mediated immune responses that typically develop over 24-72 hours. These reactions are mediated by T lymphocytes rather than antibodies and are seen in contact dermatitis and tuberculin skin tests.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType V\u003C/strong\u003E hypersensitivity is not a widely accepted classification. Some texts use this term to describe stimulating autoantibodies (as seen in Graves\u0027 disease), but this is more commonly considered a variant of Type II hypersensitivity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Type I hypersensitivity reactions are IgE-mediated and cause immediate allergic responses.","Type II hypersensitivity reactions involve antibody-dependent cytotoxicity.","Type III hypersensitivity reactions are caused by immune complex deposition.","Type IV hypersensitivity reactions are T-cell mediated and typically delayed."],"references":["Baik et al. Classification and management of hypersensitivity reactions, International Journal Of Community Medicine And Public Health, 2022, https://www.ijcmph.com/index.php/ijcmph/article/view/10547"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67492"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19063"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67492","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67492"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-29T14:26:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-29T14:27:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11797"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82294"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"39","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/39"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immunology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{